MICE Imputation Method using Linear Regression¶

Multiple Imputation by Chained Equations (MICE) first calculates the mean of every column where there is a missing value and uses the mean value as a placeholder. Then it runs a series of regression models (chained equations) to impute each missing value sequentially. Like in any regression model, MICE uses a feature matrix and target variable to train, and in this case, the target variable is the column with missing values. MICE predicts and updates missing values on target columns. Iteratively, MICE repeats this process several times by constantly changing the placeholder variables with the predictions from the previous iteration. In the end, it reaches a robust estimation.

With this approach, we predict the Missing values of all variables using the MICE imputation method under the assumption that tthe missing data are Missing At Random (MAR).

In [13]:
from sklearn.experimental import enable_iterative_imputer
from sklearn.impute import IterativeImputer
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression 

lr = LinearRegression()
imp = IterativeImputer(estimator = lr,missing_values = np.nan, max_iter = 10, verbose = 2, imputation_order = 'roman',random_state = 0)
mice_data = imp.fit_transform(df)

There were no companies with negative CO2 emissions from the original dataframe whereas out initial attempt had too many negative values, which means that the initial approach to this problem is not correct. For our second attempt, we will first impute the missing values of x variables. Then after that we apply linear regression to predict the values of y variable that is TOTAL_GHG_CO2_EMISSIONS.

In [26]:
#Test set with 6761 'TOTAL_GHG_CO2_EMISSIONS' null values
test_df = scaled[mice2_df['TOTAL_GHG_CO2_EMISSIONS'].isnull()]
